  description="Complete guide to diverting and merging conveyors: push diverters, pop-up transfers, merge zones, sortation methods. Selection criteria for packaging and distribution."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Diverting & Merging</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Diverting & Merging</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Diverting & Merging Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>Diverting and merging conveyor systems route products between conveyor lines — splitting a single line into multiple destination lanes (diverting) or combining multiple infeed lanes into a single outbound line (merging). These systems are the traffic management layer of every <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging line</a> and distribution center, controlling product flow between processes, sort lanes, shipping destinations, and storage areas. Divert methods range from simple pneumatic pushers to high-speed <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems</a> handling 300+ products per minute.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Divert Methods -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="divert-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Divert Methods</div>
      <h2 id="divert-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Divert <span class="text-accent">Methods</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Push Diverters</h3>
        <p>Push diverters use pneumatic or electric actuators to push products off the main conveyor onto a perpendicular spur. Pneumatic pushers are the simplest and cheapest divert mechanism: a cylinder fires, a plate pushes the product, and the cylinder retracts. Cycle time is 1-2 seconds. Push diverters handle 1-100 lbs at line speeds up to 200 FPM. They suit <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">reject systems</a>, simple two-way diverting, and low-speed applications. Push diverters may rotate product orientation during the push.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Pop-Up Chain Transfers</h3>
        <p>Pop-up chain transfers lift parallel chains above the <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a> surface to drive products perpendicular to the original direction. The chains engage the product bottom and carry it to the spur conveyor. Pop-up chains maintain product orientation, handle 10-300 lbs, and cycle in 2-4 seconds. They are the standard medium-speed divert mechanism in packaging and distribution. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer conveyor guide</a> for detailed pop-up chain coverage.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Pop-Up Wheel Sorters</h3>
        <p>Pop-up wheel sorters use angled wheels that rise above the roller surface to redirect products at 30-45 degrees. The wheels provide a gentle divert angle that minimizes product rotation. Pop-up wheel diverters handle 1-75 lbs at line speeds up to 600 FPM, making them the go-to high-speed divert mechanism for case and carton sorting. Dematic, Intelligrated, and Bastian Solutions integrate pop-up wheel diverters into their <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation platforms</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Sliding Shoe Diverters</h3>
        <p>Sliding shoe sorters use a flat conveying surface with rows of small shoes (sliders) that can be activated to slide diagonally across the belt, gently pushing products off at an angle. The shoes create a smooth, controlled divert without impact or sudden directional change. Sliding shoe sorters handle 200-500 FPM with high accuracy. They are a core technology in e-commerce and parcel <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Sweep Arm and Blade Diverters</h3>
        <p>Sweep arm diverters use a pivoting arm or blade that swings across the conveyor to guide products onto a spur at a controlled angle. The arm sweeps smoothly rather than pushing abruptly, reducing product impact and rotation. Sweep diverters handle moderate speeds (60-200 FPM) and moderate loads (5-100 lbs). They are common in packaging lines where gentle product handling matters more than maximum speed. Hytrol offers sweep diverter modules for integration with their conveyor platforms.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Tilt Tray and Crossbelt Diverters</h3>
        <p>Tilt tray and crossbelt sorters are specialized high-speed divert systems where each product rides on an individual carrier. Tilt trays tilt to dump the product into the destination chute. Crossbelt carriers use a small belt that runs perpendicular to travel direction, pushing the product off the side. These systems handle the highest throughput and sort accuracy. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems page</a> for complete coverage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Merge Methods -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="merge-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Merge Methods</div>
      <h2 id="merge-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Merge <span class="text-accent">Methods</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Merging combines products from two or more conveyor lines into a single outbound line without collisions, jams, or product damage. Merging is technically harder than diverting because two independent product streams must interleave precisely onto a shared line.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gap-Creation Merge</h3>
        <p>The most common merge method creates gaps in the main line traffic to accept products from a spur. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyor zones</a> on the main line slow or stop to create gaps. Products from the spur line enter the gaps. Photo-eye sensors detect products on both lines and PLC logic coordinates the gap creation and merge timing. Gap-creation merge handles 20-60 merges per minute depending on product spacing and conveyor speed.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Zipper Merge</h3>
        <p>Zipper merging alternates products from two infeed lines onto a single outbound line: one from line A, one from line B, one from line A, and so on. Each infeed line uses independently controlled zones that release products in alternating sequence. Zipper merges provide the highest merge throughput (up to 120 per minute) because every gap on the outbound is filled. Zipper merges require equal or near-equal product flow from both infeed lines.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Powered Merge Conveyor</h3>
        <p>Powered merge conveyors use tapered or angled roller sections where the spur conveyor joins the main line at an angle (typically 30-45 degrees). The angled merge section uses powered rollers running at a speed calculated to slot spur products into main line gaps. The merge angle and roller speed differential create a smooth entry without impact. Intelligrated, Dematic, and TGW offer powered merge conveyor sections integrated with their sortation and <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation systems</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gravity Merge (Wye Merge)</h3>
        <p>Gravity wye merges use two declining <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">gravity roller conveyor</a> spurs that converge into a single outbound line in a Y-shape. Products from both spurs roll by gravity into the common outbound lane. Gravity merges have no collision control — products from both spurs may arrive simultaneously and jam. They suit low-volume manual operations where operators control the flow. Automated systems should avoid uncontrolled gravity merges.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="comparison-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
