              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Pop-Up Chain</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Pop-Up Wheel</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Sliding Shoe</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Sweep Arm</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Max Line Speed</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">200 FPM</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">120 FPM</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">600 FPM</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">500 FPM</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">200 FPM</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Max Load</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">100 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">300 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">75 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">75 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">100 lbs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Orientation</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">May rotate</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Maintained</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Slight rotation</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Slight rotation</td>
              <td class="py-3">Controlled</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Destinations</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1-2</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1 per unit</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1 per unit</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">2 sides</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">1-2</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Relative Cost</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">For multi-destination sortation, see our <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems guide</a>. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Diverting & Merging <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Packaging line product routing:</strong> Diverters route products from a main transport conveyor to one of several packaging machines (case packers, labelers, sealers). Pop-up chain transfers or sweep diverters at each machine infeed activate based on PLC routing logic. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation zones</a> upstream of each divert point buffer products for reliable divert timing.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Quality reject systems:</strong> Push diverters at <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">reject stations</a> push failed products off the main line. Checkweighers, metal detectors, and vision systems trigger the divert. Push diverters provide the fastest cycle time and lowest cost for binary (pass/fail) reject decisions.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Distribution center sortation:</strong> High-speed divert systems route packages from induct conveyors to sort lanes based on destination data from barcode or RFID scanning. Pop-up wheel sorters and sliding shoe diverters handle 100-300+ sorts per minute. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems page</a> for complete high-speed sortation coverage.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Order fulfillment merging:</strong> Products picked from multiple zones merge onto a single pack-out conveyor. Each pick zone feeds a spur conveyor that merges with the main line through gap-creation merge zones. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR zone conveyors</a> provide precise merge control. Dematic, Intelligrated, and TGW engineer merge solutions for fulfillment operations.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-functions/collating-laning/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Collating and laning:</a></strong> Diverters distribute products from a single infeed across multiple parallel lanes for case packing, tray loading, or palletizer infeed. <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/shuttle/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Shuttle conveyors</a> and reciprocating pushers handle multi-lane distribution at moderate throughput.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Multi-line palletizer feed:</strong> Divert systems route cases from a common trunk line to one of several palletizer infeed lanes. Each palletizer builds a specific SKU pallet. The divert system reads case barcodes and activates the correct divert to route each case to its assigned palletizer.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Selection Guide -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Select a <span class="text-accent">Divert/Merge System</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Speed and throughput are the primary selection drivers.</strong> Under 30 diverts/minute: push diverter or sweep arm. 30-60 diverts/minute: pop-up chain transfer. Over 60 diverts/minute: pop-up wheel sorter, sliding shoe, or <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation system</a>.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Number of destinations determines system architecture.</strong> 1-2 destinations: single divert point. 3-6 destinations: multiple divert points along a trunk line. 7+ destinations: dedicated sortation system with scanning, routing logic, and integrated divert array.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Product characteristics affect divert method.</strong> Heavy products (over 100 lbs) need pop-up chain transfers or <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">turntable transfers</a>. Light, flat-bottom products suit pop-up wheels and sliding shoes. Orientation-sensitive products require pop-up chains (no rotation) and prohibit push diverters (rotation risk).</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Merge design depends on infeed rates.</strong> Single spur merging into a low-traffic main line: simple gap-creation merge. Multiple spurs merging into a busy main line: zipper merge with coordinated zone controls. High-speed merge after sortation: powered merge conveyors with servo speed matching. Always provide enough <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a> before merge points to buffer products during merge gaps.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Scanning and controls integration.</strong> Automated diverting requires product identification (barcode, RFID, vision) and routing logic (PLC, WCS, or WMS). The scanning station must be far enough upstream of the divert point to allow processing time and product travel time. Controls latency, scanner read rate, and divert actuation time all affect the minimum distance between scan and divert.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a divert and merge system?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>A system that routes products between conveyor lines — splitting one line into multiple lanes (diverting) or combining multiple lanes into one (merging). Methods include push diverters, pop-up transfers, pop-up wheels, shoe sorters, and controlled merge zones. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor types guide</a> for the full picture.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Diverting vs sortation — what is the difference?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Diverting routes products to 2-4 destinations at a single decision point. <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Sortation</a> routes to 10-200+ destinations at high speed with scanning, routing logic, and multiple divert points. A diverter is a component; a sortation system is an integrated solution.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How do merge conveyors prevent collisions?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Sensors detect products on both lines. The merge controller creates gaps in main line traffic by slowing upstream <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR zones</a>. Spur products enter the gaps. Zipper merges alternate products from each line for maximum throughput. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation</a> before merge points buffers products during merge timing gaps.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Child Pages + Related -->
